The firmness of Zenobia was supported by the hope, that in a very short time famine would compel the Roman army to repass the desert; and by the reasonable expectation that the kings of the East, aud particularly the Perfian monarch, would arm in the defence off their most natural ally. But Fortune and the perseverance of Aure- lian overcame every obstacle. The death of Sapor, which hap- pened about this time ⁷¹, distracted the councils of Perfia, and the inconfiderable succours that attempted to relieve Palmyra, were easllyt intercepted either by the arms or the liberality of the emperor.
